Non-obvious choices in this commit:

**Why the `feat!` (breaking-change) prefix.**
Removing Docker breaks every pre-ADR-023 install whose agents depended
on Docker. Per ADR-023 decision 4 this is intentional — Docker users
stay on the previous release until they're ready to migrate to c2w.
Using `feat!` makes that visible in the commit log without having to
read the body.

**Why Runtime (runtime.rs) was deleted outright, not stubbed.**
The struct had zero external callers across the workspace. Grepping
`xpressclaw_core::runtime::Runtime` returned nothing. It was dead code
that grew around Docker. Keeping a stub would have been ceremony with
no payoff — the Harness trait + PiHarness+C2wHarness now occupy the
same architectural slot.

**Why reconciler.rs was 93% rewritten, not deleted.**
`server.rs` calls `reconciler::start()` as a background task on
startup. Removing that call would break server startup. Instead, the
reconciler keeps its entry point and the Ollama-model reconciliation
(which is provider-side, not container-side) and drops everything
Docker-dependent. When task 10 lands the pi harness with real agent
launching, the agent/app/task reconciliation logic comes back on top
of `Arc<dyn Harness>`.

**Why `tasks::dispatcher::load_task` early-returns Requeue instead of
being deleted.**
The dispatcher state machine has other states (BuildPrompt, CallAgent,
ProcessResponse, Evaluate) that stay valid — they just never run
during the spike because LoadTask's early return short-circuits the
loop. Keeping the state machine intact means task 10 can restore
dispatch by just filling in the missing harness lookup. Cleaner than
gutting and rewriting.

**Why the `check_docker` endpoint returns `removed: true` instead of
being removed from the router.**
The frontend setup wizard still calls it today (task 12 removes the
UI step). Returning a shaped response lets the wizard step render
without crashing, and makes the "Docker is gone" state discoverable
for any future client code that probes this endpoint.

**Why app container endpoints return 503 instead of being removed.**
The frontend has an "Agent Apps" UI (ADR-017) that hits /apps/* with
list, get, create, delete, etc. Keeping the endpoints mounted with
database-backed list/create/delete still works (apps remain DB
records) — only the launch/logs/proxy paths that needed Docker are
disabled. Users can register apps; they just can't run them yet. A
later ADR adds c2w-based app launching.

**Why `ContainerSpec`/`ContainerInfo`/`VolumeMount` moved rather than
being renamed.**
The types are generic — they describe "launch spec for a workload",
not "docker container config." Renaming them mid-spike would churn
every import in the workspace for no functional benefit. They live in
`harness/types.rs` now and read fine with their existing names for
anyone encountering them in call sites.

**What's actually broken right now on the spike branch.**
- No agents launch (task 10 delivers the launch path).
- No tasks dispatch (same reason — dispatcher needs a harness handle).
- App containers don't run (ADR-017 post-spike work).
- Setup wizard still shows Docker step (task 12 UI cleanup).

Everything that doesn't depend on launching a workload — LLM sidecar,
xclaw bridge, memory, tasks board, budget — works unchanged. The
budget / transparent-downgrade flow from task 6 is fully functional
against cloud providers via /v1/chat/completions.

**Why I didn't touch the frontend.**
The frontend Docker step is task 12 scope. This commit is already
-2657 net lines; adding Svelte refactoring would make it unreviewable.
Back-end responses to the existing frontend calls are compatible
(endpoints respond, just with "removed" flags / 503s).

**Why `pub use types::{ContainerInfo, ContainerSpec, VolumeMount}`
from harness/mod.rs.**
Every caller that was importing from `docker::manager` got a find-
and-replace to `harness::types`. Re-exporting at the harness module
level means new callers can just `use crate::harness::*` to get both
the trait and its supporting types in one line.
